I thought the selection of guests and songs was only a middling representation of the whole 40 years of ACL. It probably would have been better to simply pick out the best of the best past shows and do an anthology. Sheryl Crow was fine, though she outright stole Janis Joplin's (IIRC) licks on Me & Bobby McGee. Did Jeff Bridges really deserve a spot to do a song? There was a group I'd never heard of that sounded somewhat like early Santana. It was a good energetic performance, but again, not representative of ACL's 40 years. Willie Nelson? Of course. Lyle Lovett? Sure. Bonnie Raitt? Yes. I would also have asked Shawn Colvin, Asleep At The Wheel, played the clip of Coldplay performing a song they wrote for Johnny Cash, and invited Rosanne Cash to be on the show. These were my thoughts watching the broadcast. I was disappointed.

I have to say, I didn't enjoy the 40th Anniversary much at all. For me, ACL's appeal is it's eclectic mix of performers, and can be hit or miss depending on your tastes. It began well, but quickly lost me. I actually fast forwarded through most of it. If a song or performance doesn't grab me, I move on. These didn't grab me.
